TTP Predictive Marker Analysis: Statistical Analysis

Chong Kim

04 March, 2018

Please read the README.md file for more information.

1 Objective

This project is based on a database that was constructed with 73 patients that have Acquired Thrombotic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (TTP) at the Unviersity of Alabama Birmingham Hospital. The goal of this project is to determine the predictive markers for outcomes related to TTP patients antigen levels.

The previous exploratory analysis indicated some significant univariate association between predictors and mortality (Other outcomes such as exacerbation and relapse didn’t show any strong association with predictors in the data).

In this report, we will go through traditional statistical model (e.g. logistic regression) and ML methods (e.g. decision tree, random forest, and support vector) to determine which factors are highly associated wtih outcomes in TTP patients.

2.2 Logistic Regression without Variable Selection

  • Since we won’t be using all the variables, we will be selecting the necessary variables using L1 and L2 (shrinkage) regularization method. The basic idea is to shrink the \(\beta\) coefficients of the regresion models so as to prevent overfitting (more information here).

  • Below we will also conduct a 5x-repeated 10-fold Cross Validation (5x-10CV) to determine the appropriate shrinkage parameter (i.e. hyperparameter) value. This will allow us to narrow down on the important variables.

2.2.1 Figure 1: Shrinkage Method

  • Figure 1 indicates the cross-validated performance of the GLM prediction model based on various hyperparameter values.
    • The performance criteria we are looking at is the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) curve and ideally we would like the ROC value to be close to 1.0.
    • Based on the figure, we can see that higher values of the mixing parameter and lower value of the regularization parameter achieves a higher ROC value.

2.2.2 Figure 2: GLM-based Important Variables

  • Figure 2 indicates the most important variables (based on the shrinkage method).
    • The most important variable is plt_stb_7
    • The 2nd important variable is time_plt_stbl
    • The 3rd important variable is ldh
    • Since we are interested in biomarkers, if we exclude the first two variables and run the analysis again let’s see if twe get any interesting predictive markers.

2.2.3 Figure 3: Shrinkage Method w/o Platelet Stabilization Time Variables

  • Figure 3 indicates the cross-validated performance of the GLM prediction model when excluding the time to platelet stabilization variables.
    • Unfortunately the ROC decreases drastically when we exlude the above variables in the model.

2.2.4 Figure 4: GLM-based Important Variables w/o Platelet Stabilization Variables

  • Figure 2 indicates the most important variables (based on the shrinkage method wo platelet stabilization time variables).
    • The most important variable is age
    • The 2nd important variable is sexMale
    • The 3rd important variable is raceW

7 Conclusion

So far we have used glm, decision tree, random forest, support vector machines, and k nearest neighbor algorithm to determine which algorithm produces the best predicting (based on area under the ROC curve) model. The objective was to train a model that has the optimal hyperparameter values and the optimal features/variables. The optimal model was chosen through iteratively training and testing the model on the sample using a 5x-10CV resampling method. Here is an overall summary of the algorithms based on the ROC values:

  • The glm model with platelet stabilization time had the highest ROC value. However, the model including those variables excluded all biomarkers except for a few biomarkers.
  • When excluding platelet stabilization time, the random forest model and knn model had the highest ROC.
  • Important variables identified from the random forest model was hb, age, and hct.

Based on the analysis, platelet stabilization seems to be the key to identifying mortality. Multiclass classification could be useful but since we only have 73 patients, even binary classification runs the risk of small sample size with larger number of potential predictors (here we have ~ 40).
